enough for an exact match

00:12:08.420 --> 00:12:11.550
and you'll get that Places
sheet that I mentioned before.

00:12:11.550 --> 00:12:13.410
And yes, I do have
a link for you

00:12:13.410 --> 00:12:17.380
with documentation at
the end of the session.

00:12:17.380 --> 00:12:19.570
Got one more example
for you, another one

00:12:19.570 --> 00:12:21.070
of these navigation cases.

00:12:21.070 --> 00:12:24.130
Some of you may have to get
to the airport to go home.

00:12:24.130 --> 00:12:26.380
Again, this is
really easy, though.

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:30.490
And since it's just a URL,
you can use any standard URL

00:12:30.490 --> 00:12:33.280
constructing library to
build these and handle things

00:12:33.280 --> 00:12:35.680
like sanitizing input
values or dealing

00:12:35.680 --> 00:12:37.300
with escaped characters.

00:12:37.300 --> 00:12:41.370
You don't have to worry about
that, and neither do we.

00:12:41.370 --> 00:12:43.850
So let's take a step back.

00:12:43.850 --> 00:12:46.280
We've had a good look
at how Maps URLs can

00:12:46.280 --> 00:12:48.050
work for you and
some of the things

00:12:48.050 --> 00:12:50.000
that you can use them for.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.240
This is great for getting our
primary Google Maps consumer

00:12:53.240 --> 00:12:58.850
use cases working for you and
your users quickly and easily.

00:12:58.850 --> 00:13:01.412
But how does this relate to
the rest of our Maps APIs?

00:13:01.412 --> 00:13:03.120
All those of you who've
raised your hands

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:05.328
are pretty familiar with
the other ones we've already

00:13:05.328 --> 00:13:07.180
got out there today.

00:13:07.180 --> 00:13:10.270
There's a trade-off
between the simplicity

00:13:10.270 --> 00:13:14.680
of delegating to another
app all this work

00:13:14.680 --> 00:13:19.180
and the power of building and
customizing something yourself.

00:13:19.180 --> 00:13:22.570
I'd like to help you get a sense
of how we can decide what to do

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:24.490
when we face this trade-off.

00:13:24.490 --> 00:13:27.340
So I'm going to walk you
through some of our deeper APIs

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:30.940
and what they can offer
you beyond Maps URLs.

00:13:30.940 --> 00:13:34.480
When you need that power of
flexibility, when you really

00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:38.830
need to take it to the level of
building a map into your app,

00:13:38.830 --> 00:13:42.230
that's when we
recommend our Maps APIs.

00:13:42.230 --> 00:13:45.110
So, you might remember
those little logos

00:13:45.110 --> 00:13:46.720
I showed you at the beginning.

00:13:46.720 --> 00:13:50.510
Well, here they all are expanded
out to our range of APIs

00:13:50.510 --> 00:13:53.990
across the four major
platforms we've got support on.

00:13:53.990 --> 00:13:55.370
We'll see how just
a few of these

00:13:55.370 --> 00:13:59.880
can take you above and
beyond a regular map.

00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:02.680
Now let's begin with one
of the most useful things

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:06.280
that you can do on a map,
which is something out.

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:08.980
You can drop markers
with Maps URLs.

00:14:08.980 --> 00:14:11.990
Using our Maps URLs, you
can just get one out there,

00:14:11.990 --> 00:14:14.540
but it has to be a search
result of some kind.

00:14:14.540 --> 00:14:17.020
And it'll either be a
single marker or a range

00:14:17.020 --> 00:14:18.490
of results via query.

00:14:18.490 --> 00:14:21.060
And it only will show you
existing places or just

00:14:21.060 --> 00:14:23.260
a lat/long pin.

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:26.290
If you want any interaction
with your data on the map

00:14:26.290 --> 00:14:29.050
beyond just putting
a single point down,

00:14:29.050 --> 00:14:31.390
you want to customize
the markers,

00:14:31.390 --> 00:14:32.520
you need our Maps APIs.

00:14:35.030 --> 00:14:38.720
So, here we're looking at
Italian restaurants in Rome.

00:14:38.720 --> 00:14:41.540
I'm going to start with some
public data to keep it simple.

00:14:41.540 --> 00:14:43.880
We took the metadata
about the restaurant,

00:14:43.880 --> 00:14:46.460
and we actually used
the rating to adjust

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:49.340
the contrast of the marker pin.

00:14:49.340 --> 00:14:51.900
The brighter, the
better the rating.

00:14:51.900 --> 00:14:54.080
And for the very
hottest places to eat,

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:57.540
we put some subtle
animating steam on top.

00:14:57.540 --> 00:15:00.440
And this is all just using our
publicly available Google Maps

00:15:00.440 --> 00:15:02.330
APIs.

00:15:02.330 --> 00:15:06.420
But I did mention visualizing
your own data, as well.

00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:09.020
So let's have a look at
what we can do with that.

00:15:09.020 --> 00:15:13.490
Let's say, if you got a high
ratio of markers per area,

00:15:13.490 --> 00:15:16.130
you can cluster them to
clean up your UI while still

00:15:16.130 --> 00:15:19.040
showing useful
information to the user.

00:15:19.040 --> 00:15:20.589
Last time that I
moved I actually

00:15:20.589 --> 00:15:22.880
found this personally really
helpful on the real estate

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:25.820
site that I was using, because
at a low level of zoom I

00:15:25.820 --> 00:15:28.700
could get a broad sense of how
many properties were available

00:15:28.700 --> 00:15:30.002
in a given location.

00:15:30.002 --> 00:15:31.460
And when I zoomed
in higher I could

00:15:31.460 --> 00:15:34.130
see exactly where they
were and tap on the marker

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:36.620
to get more information.

00:15:36.620 --> 00:15:38.390
Clustering is part
of the util library

00:15:38.390 --> 00:15:43.420
that we maintain on GitHub for
our Google Maps SDK for iOS.

00:15:43.420 --> 00:15:45.470
And then we have a
similar clustering library

00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:49.900
in the util library for
JavaScript and Android.

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:53.740
Now speaking of Android, here
you can see another case.

00:15:53.740 --> 00:15:56.350
If you want to visualize
something more granular

00:15:56.350 --> 00:16:00.730
than a place, something that's
more about the data on the map,

00:16:00.730 --> 00:16:03.162
heat maps are a
great way to do this.

00:16:03.162 --> 00:16:05.620
So let's say, if you want to
look at something like housing

00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:09.711
prices, or sea level
changing, or rainfall,

00:16:09.711 --> 00:16:11.710
or anything like that
that can be very granular.

00:16:11.710 --> 00:16:14.830
It's more about the
map than a place.

00:16:14.830 --> 00:16:16.870
These can be really
easy to generate.

00:16:16.870 --> 00:16:19.750
Just plug a data set
in, like a JSON array,

00:16:19.750 --> 00:16:21.430
and you're good to go.

00:16:21.430 --> 00:16:23.790
We will do all the
rendering for you.

00:16:23.790 --> 00:16:28.260
Heat maps are available
in Android and JavaScript.

00:16:28.260 --> 00:16:34.210
Another useful feature of our
Maps API is camera animations.

00:16:34.210 --> 00:16:35.820
Now these are a
great way to show off

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:38.580
a particular place of
interest to your users

00:16:38.580 --> 00:16:40.590
from different
perspectives, whether it's

00:16:40.590 --> 00:16:45.990
3D buildings like we have here
or local satellite imagery.

00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:48.990
Those same use cases that I
mentioned before for Maps URLs,

00:16:48.990 --> 00:16:52.410
for giving people the sense
of what an area is like,

00:16:52.410 --> 00:16:54.570
now you could take
them on a little tour

00:16:54.570 --> 00:16:58.650
instead of just giving
them a top-down view.

00:16:58.650 --> 00:17:02.520
Speaking of top
down, ground overlays

00:17:02.520 --> 00:17:06.410
offer an unlimited
customization option for you

00:17:06.410 --> 00:17:09.450
by covering the
base map completely.

00:17:09.450 --> 00:17:12.180
So here we see an example
of a historical map

00:17:12.180 --> 00:17:14.069
of a modern satellite view.

00:17:14.069 --> 00:17:16.470
We've got the ground overlay
and the historical map

00:17:16.470 --> 00:17:20.310
as pasted straight onto
the base map there.

00:17:20.310 --> 00:17:23.514
It's attached to the base
map and will rotate with it.

00:17:23.514 --> 00:17:24.930
Now this can be
really fascinating

00:17:24.930 --> 00:17:25.950
if you love history.

00:17:25.950 --> 00:17:29.610
I have some friends who like
looking at old maps of cities.

00:17:29.610 --> 00:17:32.064
Personally, I'm more of
a fan of hiking, though.

00:17:32.064 --> 00:17:33.480
So I think it would
be great to be

00:17:33.480 --> 00:17:36.690
able to see hiking trails
like this in an app

00:17:36.690 --> 00:17:39.840
without having to
deal with the paper.

00:17:39.840 --> 00:17:42.150
We can also look
towards the future.

00:17:42.150 --> 00:17:44.340
I recently read
about some projects

00:17:44.340 --> 00:17:48.360
using Google Maps to visualize
sea-level rise projections.

00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:50.610
It's really important to
think about how our planet is

00:17:50.610 --> 00:17:52.650
changing, but it
can be hard when

00:17:52.650 --> 00:17:55.410
it's on such a large scale.

00:17:55.410 --> 00:17:57.210
Personally, being
able to see how

00:17:57.210 --> 00:18:00.960
places that I knew would be
changing right there on the map

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:04.540
helped me connect with that.

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:06.880
And additionally, for
those who have the data,

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:08.420
they can just use
the ground overlay

00:18:08.420 --> 00:18:10.750
to do this and just
take their visualization

00:18:10.750 --> 00:18:12.220
and put it on maps.

00:18:12.220 --> 00:18:14.560
But I've also seen
some implementations

00:18:14.560 --> 00:18:16.420
where they used
our Elevation API

00:18:16.420 --> 00:18:19.840
to calculate shoreline
changes dynamically, directly

00:18:19.840 --> 00:18:21.810
on our maps.

00:18:21.810 --> 00:18:24.010
Now coming back to the present.

00:18:24.010 --> 00:18:26.380
We also have ephemeral
events, things

00:18:26.380 --> 00:18:29.620
that don't last a long time,
like this very conference.

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:33.520
And a ground overlay can be
used to put localized geodata

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:35.620
in the form of a
venue map directly

00:18:35.620 --> 00:18:40.650
on a Google Map in our app
that we've provided you.

00:18:40.650 --> 00:18:43.459
Ground overlays have
a range of use cases.

00:18:43.459 --> 00:18:45.000
But if you want to
customize the base

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:49.590
map itself, at scale,
that's another story.

00:18:49.590 --> 00:18:52.350
Styling lets you
choose your own color

00:18:52.350 --> 00:18:56.390
scheme for the Google Maps
that you get from our APIs.

00:18:56.390 --> 00:18:58.890
And we brought this to
mobile platforms last year.

00:18:58.890 --> 00:19:02.370
It's proven to be a
popular way to customize

00:19:02.370 --> 00:19:06.560
the visuals to suit your needs.

00:19:06.560 --> 00:19:08.750
You're going to
write custom JSON,

00:19:08.750 --> 00:19:11.240
or generate your
own styles easily,

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:14.120
with our online WYSIWYG wizard--

00:19:14.120 --> 00:19:16.170
say that three times fast--

00:19:16.170 --> 00:19:18.450
and export them from there.

00:19:18.450 --> 00:19:20.600
This is a great tool to
help you quickly iterate

00:19:20.600 --> 00:19:22.310
and get a feel for
how your style will

00:19:22.310 --> 00:19:25.880
look right there on the map.

00:19:25.880 --> 00:19:27.890
Now however you get
your inspiration

00:19:27.890 --> 00:19:33.610
for a styling scheme, the
implementation is the same.

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:36.940
Now here I'm going to show
you a JavaScript example.

00:19:36.940 --> 00:19:40.000
I'm initializing a new
map object at the top.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:41.500
And then all I have
to do is provide

00:19:41.500 --> 00:19:45.340
the style property, which is a
collection of sub-properties.

00:19:45.340 --> 00:19:49.100
And any that I specify
override the default.

00:19:49.100 --> 00:19:51.890
So first I'm going to
clear out the map a bit.

00:19:51.890 --> 00:19:53.050
I want it to be clean.

00:19:53.050 --> 00:19:56.500
I'm going to turn off labels
for points of interest,

00:19:56.500 --> 00:19:59.290
and I'm also going to
get rid of local roads.

00:19:59.290 --> 00:20:01.870
Only in this map, not for real.

00:20:01.870 --> 00:20:05.140
And then I'm going to choose
a darker color for the road

00:20:05.140 --> 00:20:08.500
strokes remaining to make some
particular things stand out

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:11.310
more on the map.

00:20:11.310 --> 00:20:14.610
Now it's important to note,
it's just a JSON blob,

00:20:14.610 --> 00:20:17.880
so you can serve it from your
site or wherever you want,

00:20:17.880 --> 00:20:19.890
and you can dynamically
restyle the map

00:20:19.890 --> 00:20:21.900
without having to reload it.

00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:24.990
No re-initialization necessary.

00:20:24.990 --> 00:20:29.040
On JavaScript, it's as simple
as just calling the set options

00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:30.870
and that's it.

00:20:30.870 --> 00:20:33.990
And, of course, this is possible
across our range of platforms.

00:20:33.990 --> 00:20:37.520
You never need to re-initialize
the map to change the style.

00:20:37.520 --> 00:20:40.800
And it's really useful to
change the style at runtime,

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:43.740
because it allows you to
respond to user input.

00:20:43.740 --> 00:20:46.770
To highlight different
things on your map.

00:20:46.770 --> 00:20:49.260
We, in fact, built our
WYSIWYG wizard I just

00:20:49.260 --> 00:20:51.360
showed you doing exactly this.

00:20:51.360 --> 00:20:53.040
You play with the
sliders in the UI,

00:20:53.040 --> 00:20:57.780
and the map is restyled
under the hood at runtime.

00:20:57.780 --> 00:21:01.350
Let's take a look at
what this style will do.

00:21:01.350 --> 00:21:02.850
Now we start with a normal map.

00:21:02.850 --> 00:21:06.150
This is what my initialization
function gave me.

00:21:06.150 --> 00:21:09.861
Any guesses what it'll look
like when I apply my style?

00:21:09.861 --> 00:21:12.570
Yeah, I know, I'm the
one with the microphone.

00:21:12.570 --> 00:21:13.260
Well.

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:14.520
I'll skip to it.

00:21:14.520 --> 00:21:15.750
I've reduced it.

00:21:15.750 --> 00:21:18.870
And it's pretty barren.

00:21:18.870 --> 00:21:23.010
But it does really highlight the
highway on-ramps and off-ramps

00:21:23.010 --> 00:21:25.080
in a way that can be
pretty useful if you're not

00:21:25.080 --> 00:21:26.650
familiar with them.

00:21:26.650 --> 00:21:28.950
You know, we can take
this further, too.

00:21:28.950 --> 00:21:34.550
One of our most popular styles
is even more reductionist.

00:21:34.550 --> 00:21:38.060
Here it is exemplified in our
transport track, a demo app,

00:21:38.060 --> 00:21:41.900
which you might have seen
around I/O. This map has been

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:43.820
simplified so much
that it's just

00:21:43.820 --> 00:21:46.760
the backdrop for some bold
foreground colors that really

00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:49.190
highlight the
salient information.

00:21:49.190 --> 00:21:52.610
But it still provides key,
useful geographical information

00:21:52.610 --> 00:21:54.860
by being a map at a
level of granularity

00:21:54.860 --> 00:21:57.461
that's useful to users.

00:21:57.461 --> 00:21:59.210
Now if you want to go
the other direction,

00:21:59.210 --> 00:22:01.310
you can change the
overall theme in a way

00:22:01.310 --> 00:22:03.110
that's a little bolder.

00:22:03.110 --> 00:22:05.402
Might catch the eye a bit more.

00:22:05.402 --> 00:22:06.860
You can play with
these base colors

00:22:06.860 --> 00:22:09.590
to match your UI or a theme.

00:22:09.590 --> 00:22:11.510
You could do this
to match a brand

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:14.690
or to match a
particular time of day.

00:22:14.690 --> 00:22:16.550
Here I've gone for,
I guess you could

00:22:16.550 --> 00:22:20.220
call it, a strawberry mocha
kind of theme for my coffee shop

00:22:20.220 --> 00:22:23.400
locator, complete with
custom icons for the markers.

00:22:23.400 --> 00:22:25.400
I'm sure many of you could
come up with a better

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:27.230
style than this, and please do.

00:22:27.230 --> 00:22:30.710
I'm looking forward to
more of your creations.

00:22:30.710 --> 00:22:35.090
Now we can also do
styling beyond the map.

00:22:35.090 --> 00:22:37.910
On Android, we now
support custom styles

00:22:37.910 --> 00:22:40.580
for polygons and polylines.

00:22:40.580 --> 00:22:42.770
These are really
useful for conveying

00:22:42.770 --> 00:22:47.050
custom geographic information
in a visual format.

00:22:47.050 --> 00:22:50.930
So, say if you're building
real-world infrastructure,

00:22:50.930 --> 00:22:55.340
you can use styled
polygons and polylines

00:22:55.340 --> 00:22:59.090
to indicate rollout progress
for internal stakeholders,

00:22:59.090 --> 00:23:02.090
or for your end users to get a
feel for when your service will

00:23:02.090 --> 00:23:03.710
reach them.

00:23:03.710 --> 00:23:07.520
And you can put custom
icons on the polyline ends

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:10.940
to draw arrows, as well
as better differentiate

00:23:10.940 --> 00:23:14.320
between different kinds of lines
with dots, dashes, thickness,

00:23:14.320 --> 00:23:14.820
and color.

00:23:19.380 --> 00:23:22.920
Bringing more styling
capabilities to our mobile APIs

00:23:22.920 --> 00:23:25.290
is just the latest
example of the work

00:23:25.290 --> 00:23:27.870
that we've been doing to give
you the same options across all

00:23:27.870 --> 00:23:30.030
of our platforms.

00:23:30.030 --> 00:23:33.420
We want to give you the
capabilities to succeed anyway.

00:23:33.420 --> 00:23:38.190
So, with that, let's zoom
back out to review a little.

